<br>
From the Sept 13th, 1999 patch message (the first one on file on castersrealm).<br>
<br>
DoT Changes: <br>
<br>
- If the monster is in melee with you, there is no change to how a DoT spell works. <br>
- If the monster is running away from you (fear, wounded, etc.), there is no change to how a DoT spell works. <br>
- If the monster is moving when the damage from the DoT is applied (happens every few seconds), it will take 66% of the damage that it would have taken. <br>
- DoT spells have all had their duration slightly increased. If the monster moves for 18 seconds during a fight, it will take as much damage from the DoT as it would before the patch. If the monster moves for less then 18 seconds during a fight, your DoT will do more damage then it would have done before the patch. If the monster moves more then 18 seconds during the fight, it will take less damage then it would have before the patch.<br>
<br>
Been a long time since I looked at that, but I can attest to the fact that dots would wear off faster if the mob was chasing you.  There was a *duration* increase to the all dots with this patch, not a dmg/tick increase.<br>
<br>
Yes, this was a major nerf at the time for druids (although it predates my days of root/dotting since my, now main, druid was only level 5 at the time).  To understand just how things worked, you also have to remember that at that time *root overwrote snare*.  Also, all druid roots have a direct dmg component, and as we know DD has a chance of breaking root.  At that time, druid's roots had a very good chance of breaking themselves instantly from the DD portion - Ouch!  Druid roots were truly broken then.<br>
<br>
Let's look at your typical root/dot experience at that time:<br>
<br>
- Druid snares mob to give him some room to work (snare is faster casting than root)<br>
- Druid roots mob, DD piece immediately breaks root.<br>
- Druid roots mob, DD piece immediately breaks root.<br>
- Druid roots mob - /cheer - It holds.<br>
- Druid dots mob with, most likely, only two dots since that's all that stack (swarm line and fire dot line).<br>
- 30 or 60 seconds later, root breaks.<br>
- Mob has to be resnared since root overwrote snare, often with the mob beating on you this time since there is no root/snare on it and it is mad at you.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> This was the real danger in root dotting - Re-snaring had to be done while channeling through the mobs melee, and often resulted in death.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
- Mob has to be rerooted (enter the pain of DD breaks again).<br>
- By this time mob most likely has to be redotted.<br>
- Cycle-rinse-repeat<br>
<br>
Of course, the mana cost in roots and snares made root/dotting pretty painful at the time.  Not to mention the likelihood for death during re-snaring.<br>
<br>
Before the &quot;reduced dot in motion&quot; penalty, at least the dot was still going while you worked on resnaring/rooting.  After that it just got that much worse.<br>
<br>
Some time later, the DD portion of root breaking root was fixed.  It was never in a patch message - Verant kept saying it was fixed for months before it actually made it in.  Interestingly enough, the bug is still evident today with the druid item Scimitar of Oak from Ssra temple - The proc effect &quot;penetrating roots&quot; tends to break immediately from the 200pt DD in it.  Fortunately at the level that this item is attainable, it's preferable to have root break immediately and just get the 200pt DD repeatedly.<br>
<br>
Slooooooow forward to Jan 9th, 2001.  Well over a year after the dot nerf.  As a level 30'ish druid fighting in Overthere, I read the patch message with amazement - Could this be true?  Root no longer overwrites snare?  Immediately my experience started shooting up.  With the mob still snared after root broke, getting a new root on was quite easy since the mob wasn't likely to make it to me in time to melee in its still-snared state.  Once the mobs were rooted, I could sit down and med up until root broke or a new dot was needed.  Stand up, reroot, and sit down again just a short distance away (since the mob was still snared and wasn't able to move that far when root broke).<br>
<br>
THIS was the turning point for druid dotting.  I felt sure they would eventually nerf this part somehow, but a year and a half later it's the norm.  As a 60 druid, I still find root/dotting preferable to quad-kiting, although many druids will disagree.<br>
<br>
But the key to efficiency on root/dotting is being able to sit and med while the dot is taking effect.  Never are you going to let the mob chase you while dotted unless you are totally oom (and many druids even have clicky-root necklace for this case).  So this un-nerf to dots-in-motion doesn't really affect me as a druid,<br>
<br>
As mentioned above, bards are the primary beneficiaries of this change - Bards don't have root, so one of their solo techniques was dot, dot, dot, selo's (as a quad twist).  Before this change, they always lost 33% of their dmg.  Now they effectively get a 50% increase in this solo technique.  That's more than fair - Bard soloing is tedious and slow as it is.  And they will still make far better exp in a well rounded group. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.showPrevMessage?topicID=1434.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.showNextMessage?topicID=1434.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1434.topic&index=19><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/softsky/addReply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"><a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.threadControl?topicID=1434.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/softsky/unread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands</a><br> <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=1434.topic>Subscribe</a> Click to receive email notification of replies<br>  <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=1434.topic>Unsubscribe</a> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies<br> </td><td align="right" valign="top"></td></tr><tr align="right"><td colspan=2><form action=http://pub102.ezboard.com/BBSForum.jumpShowForum method=post><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="1"><tr><td><b>jump to:</b><select name=forumName><option value="themagicianstowerannouncements">A